##The global oil industry has been hit hard by the new crown disease

Weixin caijingEleven

The function introduction by "CAIJING" Magazine Company Industry Report team to create, discuss the success or failure of the enterprise, explore the rise and fall of the industry, promote sunshine business

The global oil industry has had a tough time since the oil price collapsed in 2014. The year 2018 was a price roller coaster, 2019 was a relatively good year, and 2020 looks like a tough year to survive in the face of weak demand and weak prices

The King of the literary world

Since 2019, the international oil market has witnessed a surprising phenomenon: The price of the lowest quality crude oil in Oman has not only exceeded the price of WTI, but has also exceeded the price of Brent Crude in 114 trading days. This continued in January 2020, but on January 31st Omani crude was below Brent for the first time. Omani crude was trading below Brent Crude on nine of the 14 trading days to February 20, accounting for 64.29 per cent of trading days.

This is because since the end of January, the outbreak of COVID-19 pneumonia has become a global public health event, causing international oil prices to continue to fall, and brought as Far East market benchmark Oman crude oil prices back to normal and rational.

The key factor is the drop in China's transport oil, which is the main source of imports from the Middle East, where Oman is the benchmark.

China is the world's second largest oil consumer and the largest oil importer, and has been a major source of consumption growth in the international oil market in recent years. China accounted for more than two thirds of the increase in world oil consumption in 2019.

In 2019, global oil consumption increased from 99.3 million barrels per day in 2018 to 100.26 million barrels per day, an increase of 960,000 barrels per day. Over the same period, China's oil consumption rose from 12.97 million barrels per day in 2018 to 13.61 million barrels per day in 2019, an increase of 640,000 barrels per day.

In recent years, China's domestic oil production growth has been sluggish, with domestic oil production increasing by only 100,000 bpd in 2019 compared with 2018, resulting in 98.97% of China's oil consumption growth in 2019 having to be supplemented by imports. In 2019, China imported an average of 10.2 million barrels per day of crude oil, up 900,000 barrels per day from 2018, according to OPEC.

Transportation is a big part of China's oil consumption. Of the 13.607 million barrels of oil products consumed in China in 2019,3.112 million barrels per day of motor gasoline accounted for 22.87 percent of total oil consumption, and aviation fuel accounted for 8.58 million barrels per day, or 6.31 percent, according to the International Energy Agency Diesel accounted for 3.553 million barrels per day, or 26.11 percent. All three accounted for 7.523 m b / D, or 55.29 per cent of total oil consumption.

Currently, the world's total consumption of primary energy is about 14 billion tons of oil equivalent. In terms of end-use, the industrial sector (including non-combustion use) accounts for about half of global energy consumption, followed by the construction sector with 29 per cent and transport with 21 per cent. Oil accounts for 94% of the total energy consumed by the transportation industry, and is the absolute leading energy source for the transportation industry.

In 2003, China accounted for 5 percent of the world's transportation fuels, including Liquefied petroleum gas, jet fuel, gasoline and diesel, and by 2019 it had grown to 12 percent. China's transport stoppage had an immediate impact on the global oil market.

Institutions and experts largely agree on the global economic impact of the new crown pneumonia outbreak, which has led to disruptions in global supply chains and dampened global trade, as well as deteriorating investor and consumer confidence due to limited mobility of people and stagnant production, in the short term, world economic growth is bound to slow.

As the blood of modern society, oil consumption is directly restricted by economic activities. The world's major energy agencies have lowered their forecasts for global oil consumption growth in 2020 following the outbreak of new crown pneumonia.

In its second monthly oil market report for 2020, published on February 12th, the Organisation of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) said global economic growth would fall by 0.1 percentage points in 2020, to 3% for the year as a whole, and global oil consumption would rise by 990,000 barrels a day, that is down 200,000 barrels a day from January's estimate.

In its second short term energy outlook for 2020, published on February 11th, the US Energy Information Administration reckons that global oil consumption in 2020 will rise by 1M b / D from 2019, a sharp drop of 378,000 b / d from January's forecast.

The most pessimistic are the International Energy Agency. In its latest oil market report, published in February 2020, the International Energy Agency estimates that global oil consumption will grow by only 825,000 barrels a day in 2020, a sharp drop of 365,000 barrels a day from its earlier forecast, it is the slowest pace of growth since 2011. The International Energy Agency reckons that in the first quarter of 2020, global oil consumption will fall by 435,000 barrels a day on an annualised basis, the first decline in global oil consumption in more than a decade.

The new crown pneumonia epidemic has the biggest impact on China's oil consumption, and it is the consensus of all institutions to cut down the growth of China's oil consumption in 2020. According to OPEC, China's oil consumption grew by 350,000 bpd in 2019 and is expected to grow by only 230,000 bpd in 2020, from 2.77% in 2019 to 1.74% in 2020. According to the U.S. Energy Information Administration, China's oil consumption growth will decrease by 190,000 bpd in 2020, of which 14.7 million bpd was consumed in the first quarter and 15 million bpd was consumed in the second quarter, 300,000 bpd and 200,000 bpd lower than the forecast at the beginning of the year. In the first quarter of 2020, China will reduce its crude oil processing by 1.1 million barrels per day, or 500,000 barrels per day on an annualized basis.

After the outbreak of NCP, due to the demand for oil products falling to freezing point, the processing load of China's refineries dropped dramatically, with the processing load of the main refineries remaining around 70% and that of some local refineries only remaining at 30% , imports of crude oil port large number of ships, China's surrounding ports have been hard to find a tank, old tankers are also used to store crude oil. Unconfirmed reports say China has returned 50m barrels of imported crude oil. It is certain that global oil inventories will increase significantly in the first quarter of 2020 and that the international oil market will face sustained inventory digestion pressures in the second and third quarters.

Since the collapse of prices in 2014, continued oversupply has been the norm in international oil markets. In addition to self-reduction, OPEC has also joined Russia and other 10 major world oil producers to reduce production, giving birth to the OPEC + . Increasing oil production restrictions to stabilize the international oil market is not only the main task of OPEC, Russia and other major oil producers, but also the top news of the international oil market in recent years.

At present, global oil production exceeds 100 million barrels per day, Saudi Arabia and other countries still have more than 3 million barrels per day of remaining oil production capacity. In the wake of the new crown pneumonia outbreak and in the face of weak demand, the OPEC + technical committee recommended in early February a further cut of 600,000 barrels per day in crude oil production, to this end, Saudi Arabia actively pushed for an emergency meeting in February to discuss the increase in production cuts, but this did not take place because of Russian opposition. In early March, the OPEC + ministerial meeting will hold a regular meeting to discuss production cuts. Whatever the outcome of the meeting, increasing production cuts to maintain stability in the international oil market will be a thorny issue for the world's major oil producers, including Saudi Arabia and Russia, in 2020.

The International Monetary Fund (IMF) released its report "the future of oil and the fiscal sustainability of the Gulf states" on February 6, the day of the worst outbreak of new crown pneumonia.

One conclusion, according to the IMF  , is that global oil demand peaked around 2041, at 115 million barrels per day, as population growth slowed, economic growth became less dependent on oil and long term global economic growth was expected to slow, and global oil demand could peak around 2030 if energy efficiency is significantly increased or carbon taxes are imposed.

The second conclusion is that the $2 trillion of financial wealth accumulated by the Gulf states by the end of 2018 is expected to be negative 15 years from now, against the backdrop of a major shift in the oil markets, said 2034, an economist at UBS, these countries would become net borrowers and all their non-oil wealth would be depleted over the next decade.

According to the International Energy Agency, the world's current consumption of oil is 100.26 million barrels per day, which is only 14.54 million barrels per day less than the peak 20 years from now, although it is still 2041.

As a fortuitous event, the slowdown in global oil consumption caused by the new pneumonia epidemic, though brief, provides an excellent footnote to the IMF's study of peak oil consumption. For oil-producing countries, in the face of a sudden drop in oil exports and revenues, to consider and take measures to maintain their economic and social stability; for oil-consuming countries, in the face of a sharp drop in consumption, it is necessary to enhance its own resilience and maintain the stability of the petrochemical industry and the domestic economy.

The winter of 2019-2020 will soon be over, but the coming spring and summer may still be winter for the global oil industry. Oil prices will also be weak in the event of a severe oversupply, with Brent Crude average prices below $65 a barrel for the full year and the possibility of low prices below $50 a barrel.

The global oil industry has had a tough time since prices plunged in 2014. The year 2018 saw a roller coaster of prices, and 2019 was a relatively good year, with scary but ultimately uneventful, as oil prices moved out of a rising curve, but 2020 looks like a tough year to survive in the face of weak demand and weak prices.

The writer is principal research fellow of economic and Technological Research Center of Sinochem Group, Editor: Mark
